                "question_id": "w1d1_q1",
                "correct": true,
                "user_answer": 0,
                "correct_answer": 0,
                "explanation": "The Bellman optimality equation is a fixed-point equation: V*(s) = max_a E[r + γV*(s')]. It recursively defines the optimal value of a state in terms of the optimal values of successor states.",
                "tags": [
                  "bellman",
                  "theory",
                  "mdp"
                ]
              },
              {
                "question_id": "w1d1_q2",
                "correct": true,
                "user_answer": 0,
                "correct_answer": 0,
                "explanation": "The Bellman operator T satisfies ||T(V1) - T(V2)||_∞ ≤ γ||V1 - V2||_∞. Since γ < 1, it is a contraction in the sup-norm, guaranteeing convergence to a unique fixed point by the Banach fixed-point theorem.",
                "tags": [
                  "contraction",
                  "theory",
                  "fixed_point"
                ]
              },
              {
                "question_id": "w1d1_q3",
                "correct": true,
                "user_answer": 5.5,
                "correct_answer": 5.5,
                "explanation": "The Bellman backup is r + γV(s') = 1 + 0.9 × 5 = 5.5. This is the expected return for taking this action in this state.",
                "tags": [
                  "bellman",
                  "gridworld",
                  "numeric"
                ]
              },
              {
                "question_id": "w1d1_q4",
                "correct": true,
                "user_answer": 0,
                "correct_answer": 0,
                "explanation": "Banach fixed-point theorem: a contraction mapping on a complete metric space has exactly one fixed point, and iterating the mapping from any starting point converges to it.",
